-- 
Taiwan Stock Movers: Cnet, HTC, Macronix International, Wintek

-- B y   W e i y i   L i m
-- 
2011-05-16T05:44:58Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-16/cnet-technology-inc-wintek-corp-taiwan-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies had
unusual moves in  Taiwan  trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of 1:30 p.m. close.  The Taiex Index fell 94.90, or 1.1 percent, to 8,911.71.  Cnet Technology Inc. (5306)  (5306 TT) dropped 5.5 percent to
NT$8.01, the lowest close this month. The network product
maker’s board approved a plan to sell as many as 60 million new
shares via a private placement to help form a strategic alliance
and improve working capital, according to a company announcement
to Taiwan’s stock exchange on May 13.  HTC Corp. (2498)  (2498 TT) lost 3.3 percent to NT$1,160, the
lowest close since April 12, on concern competition will
intensify from the third quarter after Samsung Electronics Co.
introduced its Galaxy S II phone this month, said Richard Ko, an
analyst at KGI Securities Co.  Macronix International (2337)  Co. (2337 TT) retreated 1.6 percent
to NT$18.35, snapping a five-day rally. Macronix’s second-
quarter gross margin may fall to between 34 percent and 36
percent from 42 percent in the first quarter, the Commercial
Times reported, citing information provided at the company’s
investor conference. Douglas Sun, an investor relations official
at the company, didn’t answer calls to his office.  Wintek Corp. (2384)  (2384 TT) declined 2.5 percent to NT$39.65,
the lowest level since Aug. 30. The Taiwanese touch panel maker
was rated “hold” in new coverage at BNP Paribas. The brokerage
has a share-price estimate of NT$38, analyst Charles Hsu wrote
in a report.  To contact the reporter on this story:
